pull_request.body:
This pull request commits a CloudFormation [stack deployment file](https://docs.aws.amazon.com/AWSCloudFormation/latest/UserGuide/git-sync-concepts-terms.html#git-sync-concepts-terms-depoyment-file) to your repository. AWS CloudFormation uses the `iam-automation.yaml` file to locate, track, and automatically update a stack that belongs to the `ibra-cfn-stack` template. When this pull request is merged, AWS CloudFormation tracks changes to this repository and applies updates to the stack and parameters that are defined in the file.

> :warning: When this change is merged, AWS CloudFormation tracks and syncs changes from this repository to the stack defined in `iam-automation.yaml`. Make sure to review it. You can disable syncing at any time in the AWS CloudFormation console.

#### How does it work?
Your `iam-automation.yaml` file contains the path from the root of your Git repository to your CloudFormation template as well as the parameters and tags for your stack. When changes are committed to your repository, CloudFormation automatically updates the stack, its parameters, and tags. 

#### How do I update the `iam-automation.yaml` file?
Edit your `iam-automation.yaml` file and commit the changes to your repository. Make sure that you commit the changes to the path and branch in the repository that are specified in the deployment file.

fix: Resolve installer getting stuck on 'Loading Installer' message

This commit fixes a critical bug where the installation wizard would get stuck on the "Loading Installer..." message and the React application would not mount.

The issue was caused by a mismatch in the ID of the root DOM element. The PHP template was rendering a div with the ID `se-installer-react-app`, while the JavaScript was trying to mount the React app to `se-installer-root`.

This has been corrected by aligning the IDs in both `class-se-installer.php` and `installer.js` to `se-installer-root`. This ensures the React application can find its target element and render, fixing the bug.

**A big thank you!**
First of all, a big thank you to the new maintainers and the initial maintainer!

**Describe the bug**
The bypass sensor becomes unavailable after a few seconds with the new 0.51.0 version.

**To Reproduce**
Steps to reproduce the behaviour (for example):
1. Installed the new 0.51.0 version
2. Restarted Home Assistant
3. All sensor data seems to be present 
4. After a few seconds the bypass sensor becomes unavailable 
5. Restarted Home Assistant
6. Power down/up my Orcon unit
7. Power down/up my ESP32 connected to the CC1101
8. No dice
9. Installed version 0.50.1
10. Restarted Home Assistant
11. Bypass sensor data is present

Please provide code if you can. For example, if you are having an issue with a service call, provide a copy of the service call YAML/

**Expected behavior**
I expected the bypass sensor to behave normally using the new 0.51.0 version

18:025584
Schema
{}
Config
enforce_known_list: true
Known list

**Screenshots**

ESP32-S3 over Wi-Fi connected to EMQX MQTT server flashed with: https://github.com/IndaloTech/ramses_esp firmware.
